fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
The language may be defined using a grammar in the following way:
\text {Expr} ::= \mathbb {Z}\ |\ \text {Expr} + \text {Expr}
where \text {Expr} is the syntactic category of all expressions in the language and \mathbb {Z} are the integers.

The last two rules are structural rules (or congruence rules) that define how
larger terms can be reduced:

\frac {x\rightarrow  x'}{\text {Add}\ x\ y \rightarrow  \text {Add}\ x'\ y}
\frac {y\rightarrow  y'}{\text {Add}\ x\ y \rightarrow  \text {Add}\ x\ y'}
